orts between Canadian and Indigenous peoples. Indigenous and non-Indigenous scholars address both theoretical and practical aspects of troubling reconciliation in education across various contexts with significant diversity of thought, approach, and socio-political location. Throughout, the work challenges mainstream reconciliation discourses. This timely, unflinching analysis will be invaluable to scholars and students of Indigenous studies, sociology, and education. Contributors: Daniela Bascuñán, Jennifer Brant, Liza Brechbill, Shawna Carroll, Frank Deer, George J. Sefa Dei (Nana Adusei Sefa Tweneboah), Lucy El-Sherif, Rachel yacaaʔał George, Ruth Green, Celia Haig-Brown, Arlo Kempf, Jeannie Kerr, David Newhouse, Amy Parent, Michelle Pidgeon, Robin Quantick, Jean-Paul Restoule, Toby Rollo, Mark Sinke, Sandra D. Styres, Lynne Wiltse, Dawn Zinga  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCritical pedagogyzCanada. 0aCulturally relevant pedagogyzCanada. 0aRace relationsxStudy and teachingzCanada. 0aTransformative learningzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh  aIndigenous education TRC reconciliation residential school teacher student settler Indigenizing Indigenize decolonizing decolonize antiracism anti-racism white supremacy whiteness social justice university high school.1 aBascuñán, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrant, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarroll, Shawna M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeer, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEl-Sherif, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaig-Brown, Celia, ec